    <!-- DEFICIENCY RISK SECTION -->
    <h2 id="risk-factors">Who Is Most at Risk for Vitamin D Deficiency?</h2>

    <div class="info-cards">
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Northern latitude residents</strong>
        <p>Adults living above the 37th parallel (roughly San Francisco to Richmond, Virginia) cannot produce adequate vitamin D from sun exposure during winter months (November-March) due to insufficient UVB radiation angle.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Dark skin pigmentation</strong>
        <p>Melanin reduces cutaneous vitamin D synthesis by up to 99%. Black Americans require 6x longer sun exposure to produce equivalent D3 compared to light-skinned individuals, contributing to the 82% deficiency rate.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Obesity (BMI over 30)</strong>
        <p>Vitamin D is fat-soluble and becomes sequestered in adipose tissue, reducing bioavailable circulating levels. Obese adults require 2-3x the standard dose to achieve equivalent serum levels.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Adults over 65</strong>
        <p>Aging reduces the skin's capacity to synthesize D3 by approximately 75% compared to young adults. Combined with reduced dietary intake and outdoor activity, seniors are among the highest-risk groups.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

