    <!-- FAQ SECTION -->
    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About Vitamin D3 for Adults</h2>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>How much vitamin D3 should adults take daily?</summary>
      <p>The Endocrine Society recommends 1,500 to 2,000 IU daily for maintenance. For confirmed deficiency (below 20 ng/mL), therapeutic doses of 4,000 to 5,000 IU are used for 8 to 12 weeks, then reduced to maintenance. The tolerable upper limit is 4,000 IU for long-term use. Get your 25(OH)D levels tested to determine your starting point.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>How do I know if I am vitamin D deficient?</summary>
      <p>A 25(OH)D blood test is the only reliable method. Below 20 ng/mL = deficient, 20-29 ng/mL = insufficient, 30-100 ng/mL = sufficient. Symptoms include fatigue, bone pain, muscle weakness, and frequent infections, but these are nonspecific. Risk factors include northern latitude, dark skin, obesity, and age over 65.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Should I take vitamin D3 with K2?</summary>
      <p>D3 + K2 is recommended because D3 increases calcium absorption while K2 directs that calcium into bones rather than arteries. A 2017 study found D3+K2 improved bone mineral density more than D3 alone. MK-7 is the preferred K2 form with a 72-hour half-life. If taking D3 without K2, consider adding K2 separately.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Is vitamin D3 better than D2?</summary>
      <p>Yes. D3 is approximately 87% more effective than D2 at raising serum vitamin D levels, according to a 2012 meta-analysis. D3 is the form naturally produced by human skin and found in animal foods. All products on this list use D3.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>When is the best time to take vitamin D3?</summary>
      <p>With a fat-containing meal for optimal absorption — D3 is fat-soluble and absorption increases up to 50% when taken with dietary fat. Morning or afternoon with your largest meal is recommended. Avoid late evening, as some evidence suggests it may interfere with melatonin production.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Can you take too much vitamin D3?</summary>
      <p>Yes. Toxicity can occur at chronic doses above 10,000 IU daily, causing hypercalcemia. The safe upper limit is 4,000 IU for long-term use. Toxicity is rare below 10,000 IU daily and requires months of excessive intake. Regular 25(OH)D blood testing is recommended when supplementing above 2,000 IU daily.</p>
    </details>

